		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Usually, you would use an Emulator to do this thing since they allow you to change the volume of each sound channel individually.  The rest of the post is useless hypothetical methods which would work in theory but be very impractical.  Just use emulators...
<br />
<br />For Game Genie, you would need to reverse-engineer how the game writes to the sound channels.  From there, you could do ASM hacks to the game to turn off channels, then convert such hacks into codes.  Lots of nasty 6502 hacking there, very time consuming.
<br />
<br />Also, it's possible to separate the square waves from the triangle/DMC with soldering and wires.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


